<m1>GAIL MEADOWS:<m0>Book may<ql>
close on<ql>
publishers'<ql>
nasty saga<ql>
<m1><ue5><m2><ql>
<m1><styl>names<ql>
<styl>ruleron<ql>
<styl>indentr,6l,0,16l,7p<ql>
<ep>
<m0>   If a court motion filed last week by Miami bankruptcy trustee <m0>James Feltman<m0> is accepted by creditors, Hialeah-based Southern Book Service, the book distributor that serviced 1,000 accounts across South Florida before going belly up, will put up $750,000 to end a nasty saga that began four months ago.<ep>
   ``The court must approve it and creditors must not object,'' said Miami attorney <m0>Tom Lehman<m0> of the Tew & Beasley law firm, who represents Feltman.<ep>
   The impact will be felt across the nation; Southern initially owed 206 publishers $4 million.<ep>
   ``I'm just one of the little guys, owed $6,000,'' said Miami's <m0>Arva Moore Parks, <m0>whose Centennial Press publishes <m0>Miami, The Magic City <m0>by Parks and <m0>Miami Beach: A History  <m0>by <m0>Howard Kleinberg, <m0>former executive editor of the defunct Miami News.<ep>
   The bigger publishers included Random House (owed $700,000), HarperCollins ($500,000), Penguin ($500,000) and Putnam ($175,000). When they learned that Southern had sold its assets in January, they feared they'd never get paid for books already in Southern's hands and filed a suit forcing the firm into bankruptcy.<ep>
   ``From that moment, all property became the property of the estate,'' said <m0>Patricia Redmond<m0>, a Miami attorney with the Stearns Weaver law firm who represents the publishing houses.<ep>
   That small detail annoys Parks, who attempted to retrieve 120 books delivered to Southern ``one week before the sale.'' She hasn't been paid, can't get the books distributed and, when the mess is settled, will be lucky if she receives 50 cents for every dollar owed.<ep>
   ``The national chains (--) Barnes & Noble, B Dalton, Waldenbooks, <m1> <m0>almost all of them (--) require you to have a distributor,'' she said. ``You can't just walk in and do business with a proprietor; there has to be a middle man.''<ep>
<m1><styl>cxon<ql>
<m2> <m2><ql>
<m0>   Other firms in her position, according to court papers, include the University Presses of Florida in Gainesville, Andrews & McMeel, Smithsonian Institution Press, Simon & Schuster, St. Martins Press, Rand McNally, Little Brown, Harcourt Brace, Harry Abrams and Abbeville Press.<ep>
 <m1><styl>cxoff<ql>
<m0>  According to the proposed settlement, Feltman's accountants have until May 13 to examine the books of Book Warehouse, which paid $2 million for Southern's assets, Lehman said. And that could lead to further difficulty. <ep>
   ``There were tons of return items,'' he said. ``The assets when transferred may not have been as valuable as the initial price placed on them.''<ep>
   Stay tuned.<ep>
<m1>Topic A<ql>
<m2><ql>
<m1><ep>
<m0>   Dade School Board member <m0>Janet McAliley <m0>is not a happy camper about recent examples of freedom of speech, or lack thereof.<ep>
   When she gives the commencement address for the New World School of the Arts grads June 12, she'll focus on the issue.<ep>
   ``I want to talk about the artist's responsibility not only to expand our concept of the universe but also to defend the right of other artists to do that,'' she said. When [pianist <m0>Gonzalo] Rubalcaba <m0>played at Gusman [April 10], there was some criticism that no other musicians came forth to play with him, that they were intimidated.<ep>
   ``In this community, our artists, more than any other group probably, represent our multiple identities. They must support each other.''<ep>
