<m0>   Prominent Miami artist <m0>Leonard Pardon <m0>is getting national attention these days, thanks to a WLRN-produced public television series that is airing from Montana to Maryland.<ep>
   Leonard Par<m4>Pardon<m2><ql>
<m0>don's 13-part <m0>Faux Finish Series, <m0>which teaches viewers how to create decorative finishes for walls and furniture such as marble, tortoise shell, bird's eye maple and malachite, begins airing at 9:30 a.m. today on Channel 17 and will air daily through mid-June.<ep>
   Pardon, whose studio is in Miami's Design District, has worked in Buckingham Palace, London's House of Lords, sultans' palaces in Oman, Ugo Colombo's 8,000-square-foot penthouse on Miami's Brickell Avenue and in some of Palm Beach's more opulent mansions.<ep>
