<m1>Talented athlete<ql>
<m2><ql>
<m1><ep>
<m0>   Kudos to South Miami surfboarder <m0>Monique Echeverria<m0>, 21, who graduates from UM Friday and who just won <m1> <m0>the eastern championship of the National Scholastic Surfing Association at Sebastian Inlet north of Vero Beach. <ep>
   Come June 24-29, she'll be in San Clemente, Calif., trying to win the national title.<ep>
   The Pacific, of course, generates far heftier waves than the smooth waters just off South Beach, where Echeverria has done ``90 percent of my surfing. My hobby is to watch the weather reports and pray for a Northeast storm.''<ep>
   Her surfing start began in Kendall, when she was 12 or 13. Skateboarding friends (mostly boys) ``wouldn't let me go off the ramp'' for fear she would outshine them. One day, she maneuvered around them, and sure enough, executed the best jump of the day. Immediately, she was blackballed. ``That's when I said, `I've <m0>got  <m0>to find something else to do.' ''<ep>
